    <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

    <p>
      Losing strength, gaining fat, feeling tired — these are not inevitable. They are not simply getting older. For a large number of men over 50, they are the direct result of chronically under-eating protein in a body that now needs more of it than ever before.
    </p>

    <p>
      The target: <strong>0.7 to 1.0 grams per pound of body weight, spread across your meals throughout the day.</strong> Start there. Track it simply. The habit compounds quickly — and so do the results.
    </p>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much protein do men over 50 need per day?</h3>
        <p>0.7 to 1.0 grams per pound of body weight daily — roughly 120–175 grams for a 175-pound man. That's nearly double the USDA RDA, which was designed to prevent deficiency, not maintain muscle.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why do protein needs increase after 50?</h3>
        <p>Your body needs more protein to get the same muscle-building result it used to — a condition called anabolic resistance. Without compensating for it, muscle loss accelerates every year regardless of exercise.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is high protein intake safe for older men?</h3>
        <p>Yes, for men with healthy kidneys. Research supports intakes up to 35% of daily calories from protein for healthy older adults. If you have kidney disease, consult your doctor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the easiest way to track protein after 50?</h3>
        <p>Aim for 25–35 grams per meal, three to four times a day. A simple protein-only tracker removes the friction that causes most people to quit full nutrition apps within a week.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does protein timing matter after 50?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Muscle protein synthesis maxes out at roughly 25–35g per sitting, so spreading protein evenly across meals is far more effective than loading most of it at dinner.</p>
      </div>
